1
00:00:39,606 --> 00:00:43,276
[light piano music playing]

2
00:02:09,762 --> 00:02:12,799
[Mitchell]
"In my hometown,
I never felt at home.

3
00:02:14,067 --> 00:02:15,168
In New York...

4
00:02:17,170 --> 00:02:19,038
in New York City...

5
00:02:19,072 --> 00:02:21,374
in Greenwich Village...

6
00:02:21,407 --> 00:02:23,443
down among the cranks...

7
00:02:23,476 --> 00:02:25,345
and the misfits...

8
00:02:25,378 --> 00:02:27,113
and the one lungers...

9
00:02:30,650 --> 00:02:32,051
and the has-beens...

10
00:02:33,286 --> 00:02:35,555
and the might-have-beens...

11
00:02:35,588 --> 00:02:37,490
and the would-bes...

12
00:02:40,026 --> 00:02:41,594
and the never-wills...

13
00:02:42,729 --> 00:02:44,464
and the God-knows-whats...

14
00:02:46,633 --> 00:02:48,201
I have always felt at home."

15
00:02:49,702 --> 00:02:53,673
Joe Gould told me that when I
was first writing about him,

16
00:02:53,706 --> 00:02:56,009
not knowing
that I felt the same.

17
00:02:57,076 --> 00:02:59,245
As time went on,
I would learn

18
00:02:59,279 --> 00:03:01,814
that this was not
the only thing
we had in common.

19
00:03:08,621 --> 00:03:10,356
[radio announcer]
Good morning, everyone,
this is Dan Lomax

20
00:03:10,390 --> 00:03:11,991
with another P.A.L. show.

21
00:03:13,092 --> 00:03:14,360
What are you doing today?

22
00:03:15,895 --> 00:03:16,996
-Dad...
-Joe?

23
00:03:17,030 --> 00:03:18,898
-Uh, pardon?
-What are you doing today?

24
00:03:18,932 --> 00:03:20,300
Oh, well, I'll be
in the office.

25
00:03:20,333 --> 00:03:23,503
I'm--I'm finishing up
that, uh, story I was writing,

26
00:03:23,536 --> 00:03:25,572
-the story about that fellow.
-The same one?

27
00:03:25,605 --> 00:03:27,407
No, a different one--
Which one do you mean, hon?

28
00:03:27,440 --> 00:03:29,409
-I don't know.
-[Nora] The one you
were working on.

29
00:03:29,442 --> 00:03:31,077
He works on
a lot of them, Nora.

30
00:03:31,110 --> 00:03:33,379
-Yes, so whi--
-I know, Mama.
I was just asking.

31
00:03:33,413 --> 00:03:34,714
The Fish Man?

32
00:03:34,747 --> 00:03:36,082
Ah, yes, the Fish Man?

33
00:03:36,115 --> 00:03:38,151
Oh, Mr. Flood?
No, not old Mr. Flood.

34
00:03:38,184 --> 00:03:39,953
No, I-I finished
with Mr. Flood.

35
00:03:39,986 --> 00:03:41,521
[chuckles]
I finished with him.

36
00:03:41,554 --> 00:03:42,855
I liked him.

37
00:03:42,889 --> 00:03:44,824
He wasn't real though,
Elizabeth.

38
00:03:44,857 --> 00:03:45,892
I know.

39
00:03:45,925 --> 00:03:49,128
I mean, I just liked
his story, him.

40
00:03:49,162 --> 00:03:51,197
Well, thank you very much.
I liked him, too.

41
00:03:51,231 --> 00:03:53,099
But, no, you're right,
Nora, he was not real.

42
00:03:53,132 --> 00:03:56,603
He was all--all different
people kinda all balled up
into one. You know?

43
00:03:56,636 --> 00:03:58,071
Did those people know?

44
00:03:58,104 --> 00:03:59,138
[Mitchell] What?

45
00:03:59,172 --> 00:04:01,608
That they were made
into someone else?

46
00:04:01,641 --> 00:04:03,910
Uh... no,
I don't think so.

47
00:04:03,943 --> 00:04:05,612
So what is this story
you're doing?

48
00:04:05,645 --> 00:04:06,980
Well, this story's about...

49
00:04:08,314 --> 00:04:11,284
a fella who has a bar.
Well, i-it's about the bar.

50
00:04:11,317 --> 00:04:13,219
-A bar?
-A bar?

51
00:04:13,253 --> 00:04:15,121
Yes, a bar.

52
00:04:15,154 --> 00:04:18,258
An old bar,
the oldest bar
in New York City.

53
00:04:18,291 --> 00:04:19,792
Sounds boring.

54
00:04:20,860 --> 00:04:21,894
Well...

55
00:04:21,928 --> 00:04:24,397
I don't mean boring,
I just mean,

56
00:04:24,430 --> 00:04:25,531
a bar?

57
00:04:25,565 --> 00:04:26,966
Oh, my goodness.
Girls, we're late.

58
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:28,401
Come on.
Get your things
quickly, quickly.

59
00:04:28,434 --> 00:04:29,836
All right, let's go.
What time is it?

60
00:04:29,869 --> 00:04:31,204
Joe, do you not
have your watch on?

61
00:04:31,237 --> 00:04:32,472
No, I have it.
I have it.

62
00:04:32,505 --> 00:04:33,706
-Okay, that's enough.
-All right, let's go.

63
00:04:33,740 --> 00:04:34,707
Hurry up. Hurry up.

64
00:04:34,741 --> 00:04:36,309
Elizabeth,
get your hat.

65
00:04:36,342 --> 00:04:37,277
Please.

66
00:04:39,279 --> 00:04:40,380
-Therese.
-Hmm?

67
00:04:41,581 --> 00:04:43,616
Do you think
it's boring?

68
00:04:43,650 --> 00:04:45,184
Well, I don't know.
I haven't read it.

69
00:04:45,218 --> 00:04:46,386
It could be boring.

70
00:04:46,419 --> 00:04:47,420
It depends
on what happens.

71
00:04:47,453 --> 00:04:50,056
Well, you know,
nothing happens.

72
00:04:50,089 --> 00:04:52,892
Well, then it all
depends on the writer,
doesn't it, my dear?

73
00:04:54,394 --> 00:04:56,462
-[Nora] Come on!
-All right, all right.
Let's go.

74
00:04:56,496 --> 00:04:57,797
Here we go.

75
00:04:57,830 --> 00:04:59,699
Does Elizabeth have
her bag? Good girl.

76
00:04:59,732 --> 00:05:00,667
Yes, you are.

77
00:05:02,035 --> 00:05:03,469
-Okay. Come here. Come here.
-Good-bye, Mom.

78
00:05:03,503 --> 00:05:05,738
-Bye, sweetheart.
-Bye, Mom.

79
00:05:05,772 --> 00:05:07,373
[jazz music playing]

80
00:05:25,124 --> 00:05:26,292
[Sarah]
Good morning,
Mr. Mitchell.

81
00:05:26,326 --> 00:05:27,393
Morning, Sarah.

82
00:05:27,427 --> 00:05:29,262
Well, you forgot
the "good."

83
00:05:29,295 --> 00:05:30,496
Pardon?

84
00:05:30,530 --> 00:05:33,633
You said
only, "Morning,"
without the "good."

85
00:05:33,666 --> 00:05:36,469
Well, I haven't
quite made up my mind
about this one yet.

86
00:05:36,502 --> 00:05:37,704
[both chuckle]

87
00:05:37,737 --> 00:05:39,605
[phone rings]

88
00:05:40,573 --> 00:05:41,741
New Yorker.

89
00:05:41,774 --> 00:05:43,876
-[woman] Morning, Mr. Mitchell.
-Morning.

90
00:05:59,292 --> 00:06:00,293
[Harold] Mitchell.

91
00:06:00,326 --> 00:06:01,561
Mr. Ross.

92
00:06:01,594 --> 00:06:02,729
-I love it!
-What?

93
00:06:02,762 --> 00:06:03,896
This. The bar piece.

94
00:06:03,930 --> 00:06:06,799
Oh, oh, well,
thank you, but...

95
00:06:06,833 --> 00:06:08,835
-it's not done yet.
-Well, it feels done to me.

96
00:06:08,868 --> 00:06:10,703
[chuckles]
Well, thanks, but, um...

97
00:06:10,737 --> 00:06:13,039
uh, I was thinking
that, um--

98
00:06:13,072 --> 00:06:15,375
Well, I was thinking
that it could be...

99
00:06:15,408 --> 00:06:16,442
What, longer?

100
00:06:16,476 --> 00:06:18,711
No. Maybe. But,

101
00:06:18,745 --> 00:06:21,681
uh, no,
I don't think so.
I think it, um--

102
00:06:21,714 --> 00:06:23,916
Well, I think it could--
[stammers]

103
00:06:23,950 --> 00:06:25,084
I think I could, um...

104
00:06:25,118 --> 00:06:26,686
Thank God you don't write
like you talk.

105
00:06:26,719 --> 00:06:28,054
-[laughs]
-Mr. Ross, the meeting's...

106
00:06:28,087 --> 00:06:31,290
No, uh, honestly,
I was thinking that, um...

107
00:06:31,324 --> 00:06:33,960
it cou-- um,
it could-- it just
could have more.

108
00:06:33,993 --> 00:06:35,027
What more?

109
00:06:35,061 --> 00:06:37,530
-What?
-More what?

110
00:06:37,563 --> 00:06:39,065
Weight.

111
00:06:39,098 --> 00:06:41,601
-Joe, I--
-No, I know, I know, but-- but--

112
00:06:41,634 --> 00:06:43,970
I really think
that I could, um,

113
00:06:46,005 --> 00:06:48,775
-I could--
-You could,
and you could, you could.

114
00:06:48,808 --> 00:06:49,976
You could always could.

115
00:06:52,345 --> 00:06:54,046
True, true.
[laughs]

116
00:06:57,517 --> 00:06:59,152
[Harry]
It's snowing upstate.

117
00:06:59,185 --> 00:07:01,287
-[Mitchell] Aren't you
a skier, Harry?
-[Harry] Ski?

118
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:03,556
Are you--are you--
are you a skater?

119
00:07:03,589 --> 00:07:05,658
A skater, no. No.

120
00:07:05,691 --> 00:07:07,660
I thought you were the, um,

121
00:07:07,693 --> 00:07:09,729
The Hans Christian Ander--

122
00:07:09,762 --> 00:07:11,831
Now, what's his name?
Who's that fella?

123
00:07:11,864 --> 00:07:12,832
-Who's that?
-The skater.

124
00:07:12,865 --> 00:07:14,700
Brinker.

125
00:07:14,734 --> 00:07:15,735
Sonja Henie.

126
00:07:15,768 --> 00:07:17,570
[laughs]

127
00:07:17,603 --> 00:07:20,606
Well, you do--
you resemble her, just--

128
00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:23,309
-Brinker.
-I-I know. Bri-- Hans Brinker.

129
00:07:23,342 --> 00:07:26,145
Yes. Now I know. Yes.

130
00:07:26,179 --> 00:07:28,114
-I look like Hans Brinker?
-Huh?

131
00:07:28,147 --> 00:07:30,683
I look like
Hans Brinker?

132
00:07:30,716 --> 00:07:31,684
You guys.

133
00:07:31,717 --> 00:07:32,752
Let me get something
to eat, Harry.

134
00:07:32,785 --> 00:07:34,187
I can't wait till tonight.

135
00:07:37,590 --> 00:07:39,992
[Harry] Get me
a bowl of soup, Jimmy!

136
00:07:40,026 --> 00:07:41,861
Jesus Christ.

137
00:07:41,894 --> 00:07:43,863
[muttering]

138
00:07:49,969 --> 00:07:51,871
[mumbles]

139
00:07:53,272 --> 00:07:54,373
Soup's up!

140
00:07:58,911 --> 00:08:00,012
How do, Joe?

141
00:08:01,547 --> 00:08:03,749
Could be worse.
Could be worse.

142
00:08:19,699 --> 00:08:22,134
No more comin' in
during the day, Joe.

143
00:08:26,405 --> 00:08:27,940
You hear me?

144
00:08:34,146 --> 00:08:35,114
Joe?

145
00:08:35,147 --> 00:08:36,282
Of course
I heard you, Harry.

146
00:08:36,315 --> 00:08:37,683
You're standing
only inches from me.

147
00:08:39,519 --> 00:08:42,054
Please don't think me stupid
just because I'm unclean.

148
00:08:43,489 --> 00:08:46,225
That would be judging
a book by its cover,

149
00:08:46,259 --> 00:08:49,095
and you're far too
sophisticated a fellow

150
00:08:49,128 --> 00:08:51,430
for that kind
of simple thinking.

151
00:08:51,464 --> 00:08:53,533
♪ Ha-Ha-Harry ♪

152
00:08:53,566 --> 00:08:55,167
♪ Hee hee hee hee hee ♪

153
00:08:55,201 --> 00:08:57,270
[chuckles]

154
00:08:57,303 --> 00:08:58,704
Ah, Harry!

155
00:09:01,774 --> 00:09:03,342
[slurps]

156
00:09:12,952 --> 00:09:14,954
See you on the stroke
of 12:00, Harry.

157
00:09:16,656 --> 00:09:17,957
[coughs]

158
00:09:35,908 --> 00:09:37,376
Who the hell
was that?

159
00:09:37,410 --> 00:09:38,911
A pain in my ass.

160
00:09:40,413 --> 00:09:41,581
Why do you feed him?

161
00:09:41,614 --> 00:09:43,849
He's a human being,
Mike. What can I do?

162
00:09:43,883 --> 00:09:45,751
He's a freak.

163
00:09:45,785 --> 00:09:47,219
What can I say?

164
00:09:47,253 --> 00:09:48,754
We're all freaks,
Mike.

165
00:09:48,788 --> 00:09:51,591
The truth be known,
we're all freaks
together.

166
00:09:57,964 --> 00:09:59,432
[Gould]
Oh, excuse me, sir.

167
00:09:59,465 --> 00:10:01,067
I was wondering if I
might trouble you
for a light.

168
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:02,301
Thank you so much.
Thank you.

169
00:10:04,904 --> 00:10:07,807
Thank you. Uh, could I--
a little contribution

170
00:10:07,840 --> 00:10:09,375
to the Joe Gould Fund?

171
00:10:09,408 --> 00:10:11,711
No, please,
just a little money.
Just a little money...

172
00:10:11,744 --> 00:10:14,647
-No.
-[squawks]

173
00:10:20,252 --> 00:10:23,122
[soft music playing]

174
00:11:08,200 --> 00:11:11,671
[Mitchell] Nora, would
you fetch that newspaper
in there, on the sofa?

175
00:11:11,704 --> 00:11:13,572
All right, Elizabeth,
come on.

176
00:11:13,606 --> 00:11:14,907
[Elizabeth] What?

177
00:11:14,940 --> 00:11:16,242
[Mitchell and Therese]
It's watermelon!

178
00:11:16,275 --> 00:11:17,810
Oh, good!

179
00:11:17,843 --> 00:11:20,780
Come on.
There we go.

180
00:11:20,813 --> 00:11:22,348
-Thank you.
-Hold on. Hold on.

181
00:11:22,381 --> 00:11:24,216
I pick...

182
00:11:24,250 --> 00:11:27,019
- There we go.
- I pick... this one.

183
00:11:27,053 --> 00:11:28,220
-Oh!
-Okay.

184
00:11:28,254 --> 00:11:30,656
My daddy always said
this was the only thing

185
00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:32,958
a newspaper was good for.

186
00:11:32,992 --> 00:11:34,260
And what did you say?

187
00:11:34,293 --> 00:11:36,729
Me? I said not a thing.

188
00:11:38,597 --> 00:11:40,566
-Mmm.
-That's good.

189
00:11:40,599 --> 00:11:41,767
Mmm!

190
00:11:48,240 --> 00:11:51,911
Oh, no. Oh, no. I won't do that.
I'll give you a dance.

191
00:11:55,715 --> 00:11:58,317
Now, I can do a seagull,
a seagull.

192
00:11:58,350 --> 00:12:00,820
[squawks]

193
00:12:06,959 --> 00:12:09,028
Thank you. Thank you.

194
00:12:11,163 --> 00:12:12,698
-[Mitchell] Harry?
-Yes?

195
00:12:12,732 --> 00:12:15,101
-Let me ask you a question.
-[Harry] Mm-hmm?

196
00:12:15,134 --> 00:12:17,136
You know what fella
who was in here the other day?

197
00:12:17,169 --> 00:12:18,204
Who?

198
00:12:19,405 --> 00:12:22,241
The small,
disheveled looking--

199
00:12:22,274 --> 00:12:24,777
-That was you, Joe.
-Oh, hush.

200
00:12:24,810 --> 00:12:26,445
No, you know who
I'm talking about--

201
00:12:26,479 --> 00:12:27,713
Gould.
I know who you mean.

202
00:12:27,747 --> 00:12:29,215
Joe Gould, the writer.

203
00:12:29,248 --> 00:12:30,516
"The writer"?

204
00:12:30,549 --> 00:12:32,418
Yep, written
the History of the World.

205
00:12:33,819 --> 00:12:35,755
Now don't say I never
gave you anything.

206
00:12:35,788 --> 00:12:37,590
What do you mean,
"the History of the World"?

207
00:12:37,623 --> 00:12:39,291
[stammers]

208
00:12:39,325 --> 00:12:41,060
I'm tellin ya--

209
00:12:41,093 --> 00:12:44,196
Not like a history book,
like, history.

210
00:12:44,230 --> 00:12:47,566
But more like what people
say to each other
on the street,

211
00:12:47,600 --> 00:12:50,236
wherever, every day
in their lives, you know?

212
00:12:50,269 --> 00:12:53,873
In a-an oral history,
he says he calls it.

213
00:12:53,906 --> 00:12:55,441
Help me out, Jimmy.

214
00:12:55,474 --> 00:12:58,177
You know, oral.
From the mouth.

215
00:12:58,210 --> 00:13:00,279
Go talk to Max Gordon
at the Village Vanguard and...

216
00:13:00,312 --> 00:13:02,982
Oh, okay.

217
00:13:03,015 --> 00:13:04,784
All right.

218
00:13:04,817 --> 00:13:06,786
[Mitchell] So you say
Mr. Gould comes in here

219
00:13:06,819 --> 00:13:08,087
and leaves these notebooks?

220
00:13:08,120 --> 00:13:09,655
-Hundreds of notebooks.
-Uh-huh.

221
00:13:09,688 --> 00:13:11,457
Dozens, Max. Dozens.

222
00:13:11,490 --> 00:13:12,958
All right, dozens
of these notebooks.

223
00:13:12,992 --> 00:13:14,960
They're composition
books, like, you know,
from school.

224
00:13:14,994 --> 00:13:17,029
Yeah, he drops them off
for safekeeping.

225
00:13:17,062 --> 00:13:18,264
He doesn't have a home,
you know.

226
00:13:18,297 --> 00:13:19,665
No, I know, I know.

227
00:13:19,698 --> 00:13:21,433
He leaves them here,
and then he leaves.

228
00:13:21,467 --> 00:13:22,768
-We give him some money.
-Yeah.

229
00:13:22,802 --> 00:13:24,303
Always,
for the Joe Gould Fund.

230
00:13:24,336 --> 00:13:26,238
-That's what he calls it.
-Really?

231
00:13:26,272 --> 00:13:27,873
I feel badly for him.

232
00:13:27,907 --> 00:13:29,275
Sadie, it's a choice.

233
00:13:29,308 --> 00:13:31,076
Who makes a choice
like that?

234
00:13:31,110 --> 00:13:33,546
He did. He does.
What are you gonna do?

235
00:13:33,579 --> 00:13:35,881
People live their lives
the way they wanna
live their lives.

236
00:13:35,915 --> 00:13:37,650
-True, true.
-Give them some money,

237
00:13:37,683 --> 00:13:39,718
-food, you know,
a lot of us do.
-Mm-hmm.

238
00:13:39,752 --> 00:13:41,420
Aaron Siskind. Cummings.

239
00:13:41,453 --> 00:13:43,255
-E.E. Cummings?
-Yeah.

240
00:13:43,289 --> 00:13:44,957
-Alice, Alice Neel.
-Alice.

241
00:13:44,990 --> 00:13:47,193
Yeah, we all do.
He's a smart man, Gould.

242
00:13:47,226 --> 00:13:48,894
-He's very smart.
-He's just...

243
00:13:50,629 --> 00:13:51,697
Who knows?

244
00:13:53,833 --> 00:13:56,702
[Mitchell]
So, Miss Neel, when did you
paint this portrait of him?

245
00:13:56,735 --> 00:13:58,571
This was, uh...

246
00:13:59,772 --> 00:14:01,307
let us say,

247
00:14:01,340 --> 00:14:03,242
17 years ago.

248
00:14:03,275 --> 00:14:04,310
Uh...

249
00:14:04,343 --> 00:14:07,112
yeah.
When we were all-- Hmm.

250
00:14:07,146 --> 00:14:09,081
[record playing
song in French]

251
00:14:17,656 --> 00:14:19,058
Wow.

252
00:14:19,091 --> 00:14:20,860
That's very nice.

253
00:14:24,096 --> 00:14:25,231
[Alice] Hmm.

254
00:14:30,870 --> 00:14:32,938
I gave him
three penises.

255
00:14:32,972 --> 00:14:35,574
Yes, I see that.

256
00:14:35,608 --> 00:14:37,576
Didn't really seem
to be enough.

257
00:14:37,610 --> 00:14:39,411
-Really?
-Well, because

258
00:14:39,445 --> 00:14:41,013
I think Joe's
an exhibitionist.

259
00:14:41,046 --> 00:14:42,214
I mean, not technically,
but...

260
00:14:42,248 --> 00:14:43,649
Uh-huh.

261
00:14:43,682 --> 00:14:45,784
When I'd be watching him
at parties, you know, way back,

262
00:14:45,818 --> 00:14:48,254
uh, I'd think...

263
00:14:49,622 --> 00:14:51,190
he's a little old
exhibitionist

264
00:14:51,223 --> 00:14:53,359
shut off in there
somewhere.

265
00:14:53,392 --> 00:14:55,160
He really likes this--

266
00:14:55,194 --> 00:14:56,595
this portrait a lot.

267
00:14:56,629 --> 00:14:59,265
Well, I don't blame him.

268
00:15:00,466 --> 00:15:02,401
-It's a very...
-Yeah.

269
00:15:07,873 --> 00:15:11,176
Well, at least
I'll never be accused
of being a romantic.

270
00:15:11,210 --> 00:15:13,412
Oh, no, no, no.
There's no fear of that.

271
00:15:16,048 --> 00:15:18,117
I like it very much.
I really do.

272
00:15:20,019 --> 00:15:22,588
[Mitchell]
I'm looking for a fella
by the name of Joe Gould.

273
00:15:22,621 --> 00:15:24,290
[laughs]

274
00:15:24,323 --> 00:15:25,891
Professor Seagull, huh?

275
00:15:25,925 --> 00:15:27,660
-Gould?
-Yeah, Gould.

276
00:15:27,693 --> 00:15:29,261
-Joe Gould, right?
-Joe Gould, yes.
That's right.

277
00:15:29,295 --> 00:15:30,963
Yeah, he--
he speaks seagull,
you know,

278
00:15:30,996 --> 00:15:33,499
or understands it
or both or something.

279
00:15:33,532 --> 00:15:35,067
-Really?
-Yeah.

280
00:15:35,100 --> 00:15:38,470
-Well, Max Gordon, you know,
uh, Max Gordon fella.
-Vanguard.

281
00:15:38,504 --> 00:15:41,941
Vanguard, yeah.
Uh, he told me that
I might find him here.

282
00:15:41,974 --> 00:15:44,276
Oh, yeah.
He's right behind you.

283
00:15:44,310 --> 00:15:45,611
That's him.

284
00:15:45,644 --> 00:15:48,247
He comes in here
all the time.
We give him food.

285
00:15:48,280 --> 00:15:49,848
He sits. He writes.

286
00:15:49,882 --> 00:15:51,317
-It's good for business.
-Uh-huh.

287
00:15:51,350 --> 00:15:53,919
The tourists see
a real bohemian,
they go, "Ooh."

288
00:15:53,953 --> 00:15:55,454
[both chuckle]

289
00:15:55,487 --> 00:15:56,956
Comes in about 7:00.

290
00:15:58,057 --> 00:16:00,259
[Mitchell]
I see. Thank you.

291
00:16:01,660 --> 00:16:02,895
Hello.

292
00:16:02,928 --> 00:16:04,596
Yes, uh, this is
Joe Mitchell.

293
00:16:04,630 --> 00:16:06,665
I won't be able to make it
back to the office
this afternoon.

294
00:16:06,699 --> 00:16:07,967
Are there
any messages for me?

295
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:09,668
[Sarah] Mr. Mitchell,
it's Sarah.

296
00:16:09,702 --> 00:16:13,172
There's a gentleman
here who wishes
to speak with you.

297
00:16:13,205 --> 00:16:15,574
I don't have
an appointment
for anyone.

298
00:16:15,607 --> 00:16:17,676
He's very insistent.
He hasn't given me
his name.

299
00:16:17,710 --> 00:16:20,245
-I don't know how you'd like
for me to handle this--
-Give me the phone!

300
00:16:20,279 --> 00:16:21,680
Excuse me!

301
00:16:21,714 --> 00:16:24,016
Hello! This is Joe Gould,
author of the Oral History.

302
00:16:24,049 --> 00:16:26,785
Oh, yes.
H-hello, Mr. Gould. Uh--

303
00:16:26,819 --> 00:16:29,054
[Gould] The thing is, I was
supposed to attend a clinic.

304
00:16:29,088 --> 00:16:30,589
The eye and ear infirmary
for the--

305
00:16:30,622 --> 00:16:32,091
I can pick a prescription
for a little...

306
00:16:32,124 --> 00:16:35,027
Uh, excuse me, madam!
I'm talking to your boss.

307
00:16:35,060 --> 00:16:37,196
Uh, a little eye infection
I've been having.

308
00:16:37,229 --> 00:16:39,598
Uh, and it's gonna
cost me around $2.00.

309
00:16:39,631 --> 00:16:41,734
And I just discovered
that I don't have
any money on me.

310
00:16:41,767 --> 00:16:44,336
Uh, it's getting late
and I just wondered
if your--

311
00:16:44,370 --> 00:16:46,538
-your lady here,
your secretary could--
-Sir! Sir!

312
00:16:48,574 --> 00:16:51,443
Excuse me. I haven't
finished talking
to Mr. Mitchell!

313
00:16:51,477 --> 00:16:54,346
If your receptionist here,

314
00:16:54,380 --> 00:16:58,550
could lend me $2.00,
and we could meet
anytime you say

315
00:16:58,584 --> 00:17:00,619
and I'll pay you back.
How about the...

316
00:17:00,652 --> 00:17:02,488
[coughs]

317
00:17:02,521 --> 00:17:04,223
The Jefferson Coffee Shop!

318
00:17:04,256 --> 00:17:06,191
9:30!

319
00:17:06,225 --> 00:17:08,060
[grunts]

320
00:17:08,093 --> 00:17:10,295
Hello? Hello?

321
00:17:15,601 --> 00:17:17,703
He's a terribly dirty
little man,

322
00:17:17,736 --> 00:17:20,072
terribly nosy.

323
00:17:20,105 --> 00:17:22,074
I was glad to get him
out of here.

324
00:17:22,107 --> 00:17:25,110
Well, Sarah,
I am terribly sorry
for your inconvenience.

325
00:17:25,144 --> 00:17:27,379
Oh, it's just, you know.

326
00:17:27,413 --> 00:17:31,583
For one thing, he wanted
to know how much I make.

327
00:17:31,617 --> 00:17:33,152
-He did?
-Oh!

328
00:17:33,185 --> 00:17:35,187
He said he'd
also thought about it,

329
00:17:35,220 --> 00:17:37,723
and that 9:30
in the morning was
a little early for him.

330
00:17:37,756 --> 00:17:41,493
Suggested you meet him
at a more civilized hour,

331
00:17:41,527 --> 00:17:43,095
such as 11:00.

332
00:17:43,128 --> 00:17:46,665
11 a.m.? Okay.
Well, that's okay.
I could do that.

333
00:17:46,698 --> 00:17:49,001
He also told me that...

334
00:17:51,003 --> 00:17:53,405
I have
beautiful shoulders.

335
00:17:53,439 --> 00:17:56,408
Well, he's right.

336
00:17:58,310 --> 00:18:00,345
-[both laugh]
-Stop!

337
00:18:00,379 --> 00:18:02,948
Good night, Sarah.

338
00:18:02,981 --> 00:18:05,317
And thanks again.

339
00:18:40,986 --> 00:18:44,656
So I suppose you're puzzled
about me, Mr. Mitchell.

340
00:18:44,690 --> 00:18:47,359
If so, the feeling's mutual.

341
00:18:47,392 --> 00:18:50,429
I'm puzzled about me,
and have been
since childhood.

342
00:18:50,462 --> 00:18:52,131
[chuckles]

343
00:18:52,164 --> 00:18:55,601
Did you ever have
a painful operation
or disease?

344
00:18:57,336 --> 00:18:58,737
Uh, I beg your pardon?

345
00:18:58,770 --> 00:19:02,040
Say, "I may marry Mary."

346
00:19:02,074 --> 00:19:06,945
Um, "I may marry Mary."

347
00:19:06,979 --> 00:19:10,048
How did your father feel
when you didn't want to go
into the tobacco business?

348
00:19:12,317 --> 00:19:13,819
Well, um...

349
00:19:15,220 --> 00:19:17,990
-Tell you the truth,
he was disappointed.
-Ah.

350
00:19:20,425 --> 00:19:22,461
How did you know
I was from Fairmont?

351
00:19:22,494 --> 00:19:25,197
Well, at first,
I thought Kentucky...

352
00:19:25,230 --> 00:19:27,166
then Tennessee.

353
00:19:27,199 --> 00:19:29,168
But your As
are too broad...

354
00:19:29,201 --> 00:19:32,404
so North Carolina.

355
00:19:32,437 --> 00:19:34,706
-Tidal North Carolina.
-That's very good.

356
00:19:34,740 --> 00:19:36,608
-[chuckles]
-No, no, it's okay.

357
00:19:36,642 --> 00:19:39,411
Because my father
was very disappointed
in me, too.

358
00:19:40,479 --> 00:19:41,947
[rubs hands]

359
00:19:41,980 --> 00:19:44,049
So you want to know
about the oral history.

360
00:19:44,082 --> 00:19:45,951
Yes, I do.

361
00:19:45,984 --> 00:19:48,687
Yes, uh, first things first,
Mr. Mitchell. First things.

362
00:19:48,720 --> 00:19:53,525
Uh, my full name
is Joseph Ferdinand Gould.

363
00:19:53,559 --> 00:19:56,528
My father,
Clarke Storer Gould,
was a doctor,

364
00:19:56,562 --> 00:19:58,730
as was his father
before him, as was,
as was...

365
00:19:58,764 --> 00:20:01,500
And the Goulds
have been the Goulds

366
00:20:01,533 --> 00:20:04,469
since the Cabots
and the Lowells
were clam-diggers.

367
00:20:04,503 --> 00:20:08,507
Uh, should've been born
in Boston, but was born
and raised in Norwood,

368
00:20:08,540 --> 00:20:09,942
which is a fairly
good-sized Yankee town

369
00:20:09,975 --> 00:20:11,710
about 15 miles
southwest of the city.

370
00:20:13,111 --> 00:20:14,513
Went to Harvard.

371
00:20:14,546 --> 00:20:17,049
-Ah.
-Graduated class 1911.

372
00:20:17,082 --> 00:20:21,453
Then after Harvard,
I-I did a variety
of unsuitable things.

373
00:20:21,486 --> 00:20:23,889
I studied eugenics, which
I put to use by measuring

374
00:20:23,922 --> 00:20:25,524
the heads of a thousand
Chippewa Indians.

375
00:20:25,557 --> 00:20:26,992
Let's face it. The only
civilized people left.

376
00:20:27,025 --> 00:20:29,228
Before finally arriving
in New York

377
00:20:29,261 --> 00:20:30,829
where I became
a half messenger boy,

378
00:20:30,862 --> 00:20:32,764
uh, half police reporter
on the Evening Mail.

379
00:20:32,798 --> 00:20:35,234
Evening Mail, yeah, sure.
I know the Evening Mail.

380
00:20:35,267 --> 00:20:37,002
[Gould] Now this
is very important.

381
00:20:37,035 --> 00:20:38,670
One day,

382
00:20:38,704 --> 00:20:40,539
while I was reading
during the lunch hour,

383
00:20:40,572 --> 00:20:42,741
I saw a quote

384
00:20:42,774 --> 00:20:44,843
which changed the course
of my life forever.

385
00:20:44,876 --> 00:20:47,879
No, I'll--I'll tell it
to you at a later time.

386
00:20:47,913 --> 00:20:50,249
-All right.
-Then all of a sudden,

387
00:20:50,282 --> 00:20:52,351
the idea for
the Oral History
occurred to me.

388
00:20:52,384 --> 00:20:54,219
I would spend my life
in the city...

389
00:20:55,387 --> 00:20:56,955
listening to people

390
00:20:56,989 --> 00:20:58,824
and writing down
whatever I heard them say,

391
00:20:58,857 --> 00:21:01,059
no matter how boring
or dull or idiotic or...

392
00:21:01,093 --> 00:21:02,628
Where the hell
is our lunch?!

393
00:21:05,931 --> 00:21:07,866
Goddamn Greek
son of a bitch.

394
00:21:13,405 --> 00:21:16,008
You know how long
the Oral History is now,
Mr. Mitchell?

395
00:21:16,041 --> 00:21:17,809
No, I don't.
Um, but, um...

396
00:21:17,843 --> 00:21:19,344
[Gould] One million...

397
00:21:19,378 --> 00:21:21,013
two-hundred thousand
words long.

398
00:21:21,046 --> 00:21:24,116
That's three times longer
than the Holy Bible.

399
00:21:24,149 --> 00:21:26,251
That's very impressive.

400
00:21:26,285 --> 00:21:27,986
I think so. I think so.

401
00:21:28,020 --> 00:21:29,855
I mean, not even given--

402
00:21:29,888 --> 00:21:31,590
[Mitchell]
Uh, no, no, I know. Thanks.

403
00:21:31,623 --> 00:21:33,158
Thank you.

404
00:21:42,234 --> 00:21:43,835
[waitress]
You oughta have
more self-respect

405
00:21:43,869 --> 00:21:45,270
than to do
a thing like that.

406
00:21:45,304 --> 00:21:47,706
When I'm hungry,
I don't have any
self-respect.

407
00:21:47,739 --> 00:21:49,508
Besides...

408
00:21:49,541 --> 00:21:52,277
I-I'm not just
an ordinary person!

409
00:21:54,713 --> 00:21:56,548
I am Joe Gould!

410
00:21:56,581 --> 00:21:58,617
I'm Joe Gould the poet!
I'm Joe Gould the historian!

411
00:21:58,650 --> 00:22:01,053
I'm Joe Gould the wild
Chippewa Indian dancer!

412
00:22:01,086 --> 00:22:03,822
I do you an honor merely
coming into this place!

413
00:22:05,090 --> 00:22:06,325
And what do you do
in return

414
00:22:06,358 --> 00:22:08,026
but bother me about
such things as ketchup!

415
00:22:14,132 --> 00:22:16,201
[chuckles]

416
00:22:16,234 --> 00:22:18,904
There is a small word
for a big woman like that

417
00:22:18,937 --> 00:22:20,939
but I'll not use it until
we're better acquainted.

418
00:22:20,972 --> 00:22:22,908
Let's eat.

419
00:22:22,941 --> 00:22:25,944
-[grunts]
-Oh, so, what did you--

420
00:22:25,977 --> 00:22:27,546
-Oh. Ah.
-I got--

421
00:22:27,579 --> 00:22:31,049
Yeah, it's an excerpt from
Ezra Pound's old magazine.

422
00:22:31,083 --> 00:22:32,984
-August, 1927.
-Oh, The Exile.
Oh, yes. I know this.

423
00:22:33,018 --> 00:22:34,753
-There's a chapter from
the Oral History in there.
-Certainly.

424
00:22:34,786 --> 00:22:37,422
And, uh, I've got
E.E. Cummings
to thank for that.

425
00:22:37,456 --> 00:22:39,257
Oh, you know E.E.?

426
00:22:39,291 --> 00:22:40,859
He knows
me-hee-hee.

427
00:22:40,892 --> 00:22:42,227
[both chuckle]

428
00:22:42,260 --> 00:22:43,929
-Yeah, he wrote a poem about me.
-Oh, really?

429
00:22:43,962 --> 00:22:46,465
Yeah. Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Now here's--
What the fuck?

430
00:22:46,498 --> 00:22:48,266
Oh, cigarette butts.

431
00:22:48,300 --> 00:22:49,768
No, no, that's okay.

432
00:22:49,801 --> 00:22:51,670
It's useful
to have a sack when
the weather's wet.

433
00:22:51,703 --> 00:22:54,840
-Sure.
-Now we got-- [coughs]

434
00:22:54,873 --> 00:22:56,775
Yeah, we've got a copy
of Broom here.

435
00:22:56,808 --> 00:22:58,677
Oh, good, all right.
Yes, I know Broom.

436
00:22:58,710 --> 00:23:00,679
Now, that has snippets
of the Oral History
in there.

437
00:23:00,712 --> 00:23:01,847
Yeah. Good.

438
00:23:01,880 --> 00:23:04,483
-All right. Wonderful.
-Yeah.

439
00:23:04,516 --> 00:23:06,351
-One more snippet-- Whoa!
-And, uh...

440
00:23:06,385 --> 00:23:08,186
Whoa-ho-ho!

441
00:23:08,220 --> 00:23:11,123
-I have it. I have it.
-You got it? Thank you,
sir. Thank you so much.

442
00:23:11,156 --> 00:23:13,024
Now we've got Pagany.
Pagany.

443
00:23:13,058 --> 00:23:14,526
Now there's some
snippets in there.

444
00:23:14,559 --> 00:23:16,027
Oh, yes. I know Pagany.

445
00:23:16,061 --> 00:23:18,797
-There's a quote,
a copy of a quote.
- This one?

446
00:23:18,830 --> 00:23:20,465
-Ezra--
-That's right,

447
00:23:20,499 --> 00:23:22,300
that Ezra Pound wrote
about me and William
Carlos Williams.

448
00:23:22,334 --> 00:23:23,301
-Oh, really?
-Yeah.

449
00:23:23,335 --> 00:23:25,103
Oh, well, all right.

450
00:23:25,137 --> 00:23:26,304
-Well...
-I hope it doesn't rain.

451
00:23:26,338 --> 00:23:27,572
No, I hope not.

452
00:23:27,606 --> 00:23:29,307
-Well, that's good.
-Anyway, so yes,

453
00:23:29,341 --> 00:23:31,443
-this is good for now.
This is good for now.
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.

454
00:23:31,476 --> 00:23:33,478
Perfect.
So, uh, Mr. Gould,

455
00:23:33,512 --> 00:23:34,880
when-- when should
we meet again?

456
00:23:34,913 --> 00:23:36,381
Ah. Saturday?

457
00:23:36,415 --> 00:23:38,183
-Saturday?
-Yeah. At Goody's.

458
00:23:38,216 --> 00:23:39,584
-That's a bar.
-Yes, I know.

459
00:23:39,618 --> 00:23:40,919
On-- on Sixth and Ninth.

460
00:23:40,952 --> 00:23:42,554
-Yes, I know.
-Between Ninth and Tenth.

461
00:23:42,587 --> 00:23:44,689
-Yes, I know.
-You know all the best bars,
don't you, Mr. Mitchell?

462
00:23:44,723 --> 00:23:47,426
-[chuckles] Well...
-I think we're going
to get along quite well.

463
00:23:47,459 --> 00:23:49,561
[laughs]

464
00:23:49,594 --> 00:23:51,863
-[Gould] Bye!
-Bye-bye!

465
00:24:03,208 --> 00:24:06,178
[Mitchell]
"I have not read
anything else by Joe Gould.

466
00:24:06,211 --> 00:24:08,146
And yet, by this alone,

467
00:24:08,180 --> 00:24:10,515
he is one of the great
and genuine

468
00:24:10,549 --> 00:24:13,418
and original American writers.

469
00:24:13,452 --> 00:24:15,954
'I'll put down
the informal history

470
00:24:15,987 --> 00:24:17,889
of the shirt-sleeved multitude,

471
00:24:17,923 --> 00:24:20,425
what they had to say
about their jobs,

472
00:24:20,459 --> 00:24:23,829
love affairs,
victuals, sprees,

473
00:24:23,862 --> 00:24:26,665
scrapes, and sorrows.

474
00:24:26,698 --> 00:24:31,002
The Oral History is a great
hodgepodge and kitchen midden

475
00:24:31,036 --> 00:24:34,005
of hearsay,
a repository of jabber,

476
00:24:34,039 --> 00:24:37,008
an omnium-gatherum
of bushwa...

477
00:24:37,042 --> 00:24:39,978
gab, palaver, hogwash,

478
00:24:40,011 --> 00:24:41,713
flapdoodle, and malarkey,

479
00:24:41,746 --> 00:24:45,350
the fruit of more than
20,000 conversations.

480
00:24:45,383 --> 00:24:48,653
What people say is history,'
Gould says,

481
00:24:48,687 --> 00:24:50,589
'what we used to think
was history,

482
00:24:50,622 --> 00:24:54,092
is only formal history
and largely false.

483
00:24:54,125 --> 00:24:57,295
I'll put down
the informal history,

484
00:24:57,329 --> 00:25:00,232
or I'll perish
in the attempt.'"

485
00:25:02,100 --> 00:25:04,436
[Mitchell]
Maybe he was afraid.

486
00:25:04,469 --> 00:25:05,837
Maybe.

487
00:25:06,905 --> 00:25:08,540
I mean, did you
sneak up on him?

488
00:25:08,573 --> 00:25:09,641
Joe!

489
00:25:09,674 --> 00:25:10,876
No, well, I'm just saying,

490
00:25:10,909 --> 00:25:12,210
I mean, it could've
felt like that to him.

491
00:25:12,244 --> 00:25:13,578
I was
practically invisible.

492
00:25:13,612 --> 00:25:15,647
No, honey, you're
too attractive
to be invisible.

493
00:25:15,680 --> 00:25:17,382
-Oh, well, thank you very much.
-That's okay.

494
00:25:17,415 --> 00:25:19,518
No, he jumped up
and berated me.

495
00:25:19,551 --> 00:25:21,553
"How dare you?!
I don't know you!"

496
00:25:21,586 --> 00:25:23,154
I was terribly
embarrassed.

497
00:25:23,188 --> 00:25:26,191
Well, some people feel
it steals your soul.

498
00:25:26,224 --> 00:25:28,927
Now, why would I
want his soul?

499
00:25:28,960 --> 00:25:31,329
Where would I put it?

500
00:25:35,166 --> 00:25:38,236
You're a pretty funny
young lady, aren't you?

501
00:25:39,804 --> 00:25:41,606
Sometimes.

502
00:25:41,640 --> 00:25:43,875
[Gould]
Is she your type?

503
00:25:43,909 --> 00:25:45,310
[Mitchell]
Parts of her.

504
00:25:49,014 --> 00:25:50,715
I like her entirety.

505
00:25:52,183 --> 00:25:53,718
I love her, in fact.

506
00:25:54,786 --> 00:25:58,189
But... I know her,
of course.

507
00:25:58,223 --> 00:26:00,592
-How do you mean?
-Oh, I don't mean
in the biblical sense.

508
00:26:01,726 --> 00:26:03,395
Although, I swear
it got very close one time

509
00:26:03,428 --> 00:26:05,397
between me and her
on one rainy afternoon.

510
00:26:05,430 --> 00:26:07,866
There was a tension aroused
so palpable, you could've...

511
00:26:07,899 --> 00:26:09,601
tripped on it.

512
00:26:09,634 --> 00:26:12,103
No, no.
I meant that, uh...

513
00:26:12,137 --> 00:26:14,773
I know her, because...

514
00:26:16,141 --> 00:26:18,009
Gaston Lachaise,
the sculptor...

515
00:26:19,978 --> 00:26:21,746
is a friend and
supporter of mine.

516
00:26:21,780 --> 00:26:23,715
[Mitchell]
Oh, really?

517
00:26:25,984 --> 00:26:27,652
You don't believe me?

518
00:26:27,686 --> 00:26:30,388
No, that's not--
Uh, yes, I mean, that's
not what I meant by it.

519
00:26:30,422 --> 00:26:31,856
Well, what did
"really" mean?

520
00:26:31,890 --> 00:26:33,325
No, it just meant,
"really."

521
00:26:33,358 --> 00:26:35,160
An expression of shock.

522
00:26:35,193 --> 00:26:38,263
No, not at all, Mr. Gould.
It was an expression that...

523
00:26:38,296 --> 00:26:39,698
I was impressed.

524
00:26:42,133 --> 00:26:43,134
Really?

525
00:26:44,202 --> 00:26:45,537
Yes.

526
00:26:47,739 --> 00:26:49,908
So anyway, you're saying
that this fella Lachaise...

527
00:26:49,941 --> 00:26:51,876
Yes, Lachaise.
Lachaise.

528
00:26:51,910 --> 00:26:54,245
-Is a supporter of yours?
-He is a supporter of mine.

529
00:26:54,279 --> 00:26:57,315
and he took up cudgels
on my behalf in a soiree
one evening,

530
00:26:57,349 --> 00:27:01,553
when Edward Nagle
called me a barbarian.

531
00:27:01,586 --> 00:27:05,357
Because I didn't see
a picture as a picture,
it didn't mean anything to me.

532
00:27:05,390 --> 00:27:07,292
All I saw was
the expression of the man
who had painted it.

533
00:27:07,325 --> 00:27:08,893
And Gaston Lachaise
agreed with me,

534
00:27:08,927 --> 00:27:11,096
saying that art is
essentially a means
of self-expression,

535
00:27:11,129 --> 00:27:13,999
putting E. Nagle
in his place.

536
00:27:14,032 --> 00:27:15,300
[both chuckle]

537
00:27:15,333 --> 00:27:16,635
Well, that must have
made you feel good.

538
00:27:16,668 --> 00:27:18,269
No, actually it
made me feel bad.

539
00:27:18,303 --> 00:27:20,639
Because although
our thoughts were the same,

540
00:27:20,672 --> 00:27:22,374
Gaston's and mine,
his meant something

541
00:27:22,407 --> 00:27:23,975
because he was
who he was.

542
00:27:24,009 --> 00:27:25,443
Mine meant nothing,

543
00:27:25,477 --> 00:27:27,512
because I was who I am.

544
00:27:29,881 --> 00:27:31,049
I see.

545
00:27:33,718 --> 00:27:35,553
You know, Mr. Gould,

546
00:27:35,587 --> 00:27:37,389
if you publish
the Oral History,

547
00:27:37,422 --> 00:27:40,392
you might become
someone who people know.

548
00:27:41,726 --> 00:27:43,828
Oh, is that
what it's all about?

549
00:27:43,862 --> 00:27:46,564
Well, no, no, I'm
just saying that,

550
00:27:46,598 --> 00:27:47,899
if you wanted that.

551
00:27:47,932 --> 00:27:49,734
I'm not saying that
that's what it's ab--

552
00:27:49,768 --> 00:27:50,935
That's-- that's my hat.

553
00:27:54,739 --> 00:27:56,341
-Um...
-Mr. Mitchell,

554
00:27:56,374 --> 00:27:59,077
I have lugged
the Oral History

555
00:27:59,110 --> 00:28:01,713
into 14 different
publishing offices,

556
00:28:01,746 --> 00:28:03,548
and none would have it.

557
00:28:03,581 --> 00:28:05,016
So you have done that?

558
00:28:05,050 --> 00:28:06,851
Well, yes, I have done that,
and none of them
would have it.

559
00:28:06,885 --> 00:28:09,888
Mr. Gould,
when might I see some
of the Oral History?

560
00:28:09,921 --> 00:28:11,423
Why, I...

561
00:28:11,456 --> 00:28:14,159
thought you'd never ask,
Mr. Mitchell.

562
00:28:15,894 --> 00:28:18,697
Vivian! We're going!

563
00:28:19,764 --> 00:28:21,766
Okay. Bye-bye.

564
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:24,202
-It was so nice to meet you.
-It was nice to meet you, too.

565
00:28:24,235 --> 00:28:26,438
-[mumbles]
-Oh, yes.

566
00:28:29,340 --> 00:28:30,475
She's just, uh...

567
00:28:32,210 --> 00:28:34,279
Thanks. Thanks.
That'll come in handy.

568
00:28:34,312 --> 00:28:36,181
-Great show. Congrats.
-Oh, thank you.

569
00:28:36,214 --> 00:28:38,483
Bye-bye, Joe and Joe.
[chuckles]

570
00:28:40,218 --> 00:28:42,620
[Gould] I keep chapters
of the Oral History

571
00:28:42,654 --> 00:28:44,956
stored with friends and
colleagues around town.

572
00:28:44,989 --> 00:28:48,660
These are mostly artists
who understand the importance

573
00:28:48,693 --> 00:28:51,963
of what I'm doing and who are
also regular contributors

574
00:28:51,996 --> 00:28:53,531
to the Joe Gould Fund.

575
00:28:57,235 --> 00:29:00,004
Helen? Helen,
it's Joe Gould.

576
00:29:00,004 --> 00:29:02,340
I need to pick up
a few volumes
of the O.H.

577
00:29:03,975 --> 00:29:05,543
-Sweetheart.
-[Helen] Oh, hi, Joe.

578
00:29:05,577 --> 00:29:08,513
-I need to pick up
a few volumes of the O.H.
-Oh, sure.

579
00:29:08,546 --> 00:29:10,849
I have need of them now.
At least...

580
00:29:10,882 --> 00:29:12,517
Mr. Mitchell,
my biographer, does.

581
00:29:12,550 --> 00:29:13,885
-[Helen] Who?
-Mr. Mitchell!

582
00:29:13,918 --> 00:29:16,588
My biographer.

583
00:29:16,621 --> 00:29:19,157
He's with me now.
He writes for
The New Yorker.

584
00:29:19,190 --> 00:29:20,825
[clatter]

585
00:29:22,026 --> 00:29:24,996
-[clatter, cat meowing]
-[Helen] Oh! Here.

586
00:29:26,431 --> 00:29:27,432
Here.

587
00:29:27,465 --> 00:29:28,666
-Those are--
-Two, right?

588
00:29:28,700 --> 00:29:29,768
Yes, yes, yes.

589
00:29:29,801 --> 00:29:32,103
Yes, these are the ones.
Uh, Joe Mitchell.

590
00:29:32,137 --> 00:29:34,339
-Uh, Helen Maris.
-How do you do? Pleasure.

591
00:29:34,372 --> 00:29:37,142
Um, do you have--
[clears throat]

592
00:29:37,175 --> 00:29:39,444
Would you have
a little contribution
to the Joe Gould Fund?

593
00:29:39,477 --> 00:29:44,182
[hums a tune]

594
00:29:44,215 --> 00:29:47,152
Yes! This will
come in handy.

595
00:29:47,185 --> 00:29:48,720
Did you think
I forgot, Joe?

596
00:29:48,753 --> 00:29:50,421
Well, I know you have
a lot on your mind, so...

597
00:29:50,455 --> 00:29:52,357
-[chuckles]
-Good luck, Mr. Mitchell.

598
00:29:52,390 --> 00:29:53,691
Thank you very much.

599
00:29:53,725 --> 00:29:55,760
She's a good egg, but
she's a little... ehh...

600
00:30:26,724 --> 00:30:28,359
[Mitchell]
N-no, you can trust me.

601
00:30:28,393 --> 00:30:29,661
[Gould] I hope so.

602
00:30:29,694 --> 00:30:31,696
'Cause should they fall
into the wrong hands,

603
00:30:31,729 --> 00:30:33,364
my plans for them
will be destroyed.

604
00:30:33,398 --> 00:30:35,967
-[Mitchell] Your plan?
-[Gould] Yes, my will, my will.

605
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:37,535
Two thirds
of the Oral History

606
00:30:37,569 --> 00:30:39,504
I bequeath
to Harvard alma mater

607
00:30:39,537 --> 00:30:41,172
and the other third
to the Smithsonian.

608
00:30:41,206 --> 00:30:42,273
Unless I publish it
first, of course.

609
00:30:42,307 --> 00:30:43,608
Oh, of course, Mr. Gould.

610
00:30:43,641 --> 00:30:45,043
-Joe.
-Yes?

611
00:30:45,076 --> 00:30:46,177
No, call me Joe now.

612
00:30:46,211 --> 00:30:47,679
Oh, oh.
All right, all right.

613
00:30:47,712 --> 00:30:49,180
-Joe.
-That's good. That's good.

614
00:30:49,214 --> 00:30:50,648
Now where the fuck
are we?

615
00:30:50,682 --> 00:30:52,984
Uh, I don't know,
Well, tell me where
we're headed

616
00:30:53,017 --> 00:30:54,252
'cause I need to catch
a train uptown...

617
00:30:54,285 --> 00:30:56,521
I know, I know. Aha!

618
00:30:56,554 --> 00:30:57,922
Raah!

619
00:30:57,956 --> 00:31:01,125
Well, hold--
Where are we headed?

620
00:31:01,159 --> 00:31:04,295
-Hold on!
-[Gould yells]

621
00:31:04,329 --> 00:31:06,631
Sons of bitches!
I knew it was tonight.

622
00:31:06,664 --> 00:31:08,700
They tried to tell me
it wasn't happening,
the fuckers.

623
00:31:08,733 --> 00:31:10,802
They're afraid.
Let's go.

624
00:31:10,835 --> 00:31:12,570
Well, Joe, no,
I really should be moving on.

625
00:31:12,604 --> 00:31:14,505
-Come on, come on!
-All right, all right,
all right.

626
00:31:14,539 --> 00:31:16,341
-Follow me.
-All right.

627
00:31:18,810 --> 00:31:22,180
"Let none of this
come to pass.

628
00:31:22,213 --> 00:31:24,782
Let the woodcutter
awaken...

629
00:31:26,117 --> 00:31:28,686
Let Abraham come
with his axe..."

630
00:31:28,720 --> 00:31:30,121
Oh, Freddie!

631
00:31:30,154 --> 00:31:32,390
Do you know
Mr. Joseph Mitchell,
the writer?

632
00:31:32,423 --> 00:31:33,892
-Shh!
-I'm introducing him!

633
00:31:33,925 --> 00:31:35,693
-This is Mr. Mitchell.
-How do you do?

634
00:31:35,727 --> 00:31:38,263
Welcome.
Francis Lambert McCrudden.

635
00:31:38,296 --> 00:31:41,299
-You're here with--
-Yes! He's here with the rummy!

636
00:31:41,332 --> 00:31:43,501
-He's my biographer.
-Oh, is that so?

637
00:31:43,534 --> 00:31:45,436
It is so.
It is--
Tell him, Joe.

638
00:31:45,470 --> 00:31:47,305
[whispering]
Yes, it is true.

639
00:31:47,338 --> 00:31:49,607
I am--
I am going to write
a little something,

640
00:31:49,641 --> 00:31:51,542
-uh, about Mr. Gould.
-[woman shushes]

641
00:31:51,576 --> 00:31:52,944
If I can-- Yes,
I'm terribly sorry.

642
00:31:52,977 --> 00:31:56,881
Mr. Gould,
though not a member,
comes quite often.

643
00:31:56,915 --> 00:31:59,417
But I don't think
it's for the poetry

644
00:31:59,450 --> 00:32:01,386
as much as for
the food and wine.

645
00:32:01,419 --> 00:32:04,422
Mr. Gould is not serious
about poetry.

646
00:32:04,455 --> 00:32:06,524
Oh, is that why you won't
let me join The Raven?

647
00:32:06,557 --> 00:32:08,927
'Cause I'm not
serious enough
for you, Frank?

648
00:32:08,960 --> 00:32:11,195
-Shh!
-Most of your members
are not serious.

649
00:32:11,229 --> 00:32:13,464
They write about
such trite themes as...

650
00:32:13,498 --> 00:32:15,300
life, love, and death.

651
00:32:16,734 --> 00:32:18,002
-Thank you!
-Yeah!

652
00:32:18,036 --> 00:32:21,005
-[Gould yells]
-Thank you, thank you!

653
00:32:22,440 --> 00:32:26,844
-[Gould continues yelling]
-Thank you, thank you!

654
00:32:26,878 --> 00:32:28,846
-Mr. Gould!
-I have a poem!

655
00:32:28,880 --> 00:32:30,548
-Yes, I'm sure you do.
-[grunting] Yeah!
I have a poem.

656
00:32:30,581 --> 00:32:32,550
But we have some business
to attend to.

657
00:32:32,583 --> 00:32:35,486
I have a poem
about religion,
short and sweet, like me.

658
00:32:35,520 --> 00:32:38,056
"My Religion,"
by Joseph Ferdinand Gould.

659
00:32:38,089 --> 00:32:40,425
"In the winter,
I'm a Buddhist,

660
00:32:40,458 --> 00:32:44,662
In the summer,
I'm a nudist!"

661
00:32:44,696 --> 00:32:47,999
-[crowd groans]
-Please!

662
00:32:48,032 --> 00:32:50,702
Oh! Don't touch me!
Thank you!

663
00:32:50,735 --> 00:32:51,669
Excuse me, sir.

664
00:32:54,105 --> 00:32:55,306
Fuckers!

665
00:33:08,453 --> 00:33:10,655
Take care of those
composition books, Joe.

666
00:33:11,856 --> 00:33:14,892
The Oral History
is my rope, my scaffold.

667
00:33:16,060 --> 00:33:19,030
My bed, my board,
my wife, my floozy.

668
00:33:20,264 --> 00:33:22,166
My wound
and the salt on it.

669
00:33:22,200 --> 00:33:24,535
My whiskey,
my aspirin.

670
00:33:24,569 --> 00:33:26,404
My rock
and my salvation.

671
00:33:27,638 --> 00:33:30,041
It's the only thing
that matters a damn to me.

672
00:33:31,376 --> 00:33:32,977
All else is dross.

673
00:33:49,027 --> 00:33:51,696
[Gould] Civilization
brings distinctions of caste

674
00:33:51,729 --> 00:33:53,931
apart from
individual attainment.

675
00:33:53,965 --> 00:33:57,869
Thus is developed
the patrician and the peasant.

676
00:33:57,902 --> 00:33:59,971
Each has a different set
of virtues,

677
00:34:00,004 --> 00:34:03,775
and both are needed for
the complete sum of humanity.

678
00:34:03,808 --> 00:34:06,511
When you find a patrician
without pride

679
00:34:06,544 --> 00:34:08,413
or a peasant without avarice,

680
00:34:08,446 --> 00:34:11,416
you get very nearly
the perfect person.

681
00:34:12,583 --> 00:34:14,285
In the eyes
of the infinite...

682
00:34:15,953 --> 00:34:19,557
all pride is
just dust and ashes.

683
00:34:25,363 --> 00:34:28,466
Ooh-hoo! Ah!

684
00:34:33,504 --> 00:34:35,840
Oh, gorgeous!

685
00:34:35,873 --> 00:34:39,710
Come on in, sweetheart,
and you drink till you drop.

686
00:34:42,980 --> 00:34:44,682
-Ooh!
-Can I, uh--

687
00:34:44,715 --> 00:34:46,918
Cummings said
there was a soiree.

688
00:34:46,951 --> 00:34:48,853
-Of course, Joe. Come in.
-Can I come in?

689
00:34:48,886 --> 00:34:50,655
-Do you mind if I come in?
-Oh, yes, yes.

690
00:34:50,688 --> 00:34:52,857
-Is he here?
-No, not yet. How have you been?

691
00:34:52,890 --> 00:34:55,460
Oh, good, good.
Spending time
with my biographer.

692
00:34:55,493 --> 00:34:56,594
-Oh, really?
-Yeah.

693
00:34:56,627 --> 00:34:58,129
Mr. Mitchell's
with The New Yorker.

694
00:34:58,162 --> 00:34:59,797
-Hi.
-Charmed.

695
00:34:59,831 --> 00:35:02,333
You've got to meet
David and Janet, darling.
They're reporters.

696
00:35:02,366 --> 00:35:04,202
David, Janet,
this is Joseph Gould.

697
00:35:04,235 --> 00:35:06,204
Joe's a writer. He used
to write for The Times.

698
00:35:06,237 --> 00:35:08,139
-Oh, right.
-Darling, excuse me a moment.

699
00:35:08,172 --> 00:35:09,841
-Good to see you, Joe.
-Yeah!

700
00:35:09,874 --> 00:35:11,943
-So you write?
-No, I don't.

701
00:35:11,976 --> 00:35:13,711
-Oh, I thought she said--
-No, no, no.

702
00:35:13,744 --> 00:35:16,280
I don't read
The Times, either.

703
00:35:16,314 --> 00:35:18,583
However, I do use it
to keep my crotch warm

704
00:35:18,616 --> 00:35:20,251
on these frigid
New York nights.

705
00:35:20,284 --> 00:35:21,519
[squawks]

706
00:35:21,552 --> 00:35:24,355
[indistinct chatter]

707
00:35:33,698 --> 00:35:35,299
[Freddie]
Heh heh. Hello, Joe.

708
00:35:35,333 --> 00:35:36,634
Hello, Freddie,
you old goat.

709
00:35:39,103 --> 00:35:42,206
Margaret, you have
just been kissed
by Joe Gould.

710
00:35:42,240 --> 00:35:44,142
I'm just gonna
go on kissing.

711
00:35:44,175 --> 00:35:46,577
Hello, Joe Gould.

712
00:35:47,712 --> 00:35:49,280
Hello, Margaret!

713
00:35:49,313 --> 00:35:51,282
[laughter]

714
00:35:51,315 --> 00:35:54,218
Joseph Ferdinand Gould.
That's me.

715
00:35:54,252 --> 00:35:55,920
Joseph Ferdinand Gould.

716
00:35:55,953 --> 00:35:58,623
Historian, aesthete...

717
00:35:58,656 --> 00:36:01,359
And though a direct
descendant of William
the Conqueror,

718
00:36:01,392 --> 00:36:03,761
I've always wanted
to think of myself

719
00:36:03,794 --> 00:36:06,197
as belonging
to the masses,
not the classes.

720
00:36:06,230 --> 00:36:07,899
A certain lady
once said to me,

721
00:36:07,932 --> 00:36:09,567
"Mr. Gould, you know,
there are two types
of gentlemen.

722
00:36:09,600 --> 00:36:11,068
One is a gentleman
by the grace of God,

723
00:36:11,102 --> 00:36:12,403
and the other
is a gentleman

724
00:36:12,436 --> 00:36:14,105
because of
inherited culture.

725
00:36:14,138 --> 00:36:15,339
You belong
to both types.

726
00:36:15,373 --> 00:36:17,708
Well,
how right she was.

727
00:36:17,742 --> 00:36:19,310
[laughs]

728
00:36:19,343 --> 00:36:20,811
You...

729
00:36:21,946 --> 00:36:23,848
All right, everybody!

730
00:36:23,881 --> 00:36:28,119
All those in favor of
a one-man show, say, "Aye!"

731
00:36:29,487 --> 00:36:30,821
Well, if you insist...

732
00:36:31,889 --> 00:36:33,558
All right, everybody!

733
00:36:33,591 --> 00:36:35,359
-Come on. Turn that off!
-[crowd groans]

734
00:36:35,393 --> 00:36:36,394
Come on! Give me this!

735
00:36:36,427 --> 00:36:38,462
[clamoring]

736
00:36:39,730 --> 00:36:42,366
-Come on! Oh!
-[shrieks]

737
00:36:42,400 --> 00:36:45,703
Okay. This one's
for Margaret.

738
00:36:45,736 --> 00:36:48,806
The most beautiful girl
I've seen in ten years!

739
00:36:48,839 --> 00:36:51,075
-[man] Come on, Joe!
-So!

740
00:36:51,108 --> 00:36:53,044
This is an excerpt...

741
00:36:54,512 --> 00:36:57,181
from the Oral History
of the World...

742
00:36:57,215 --> 00:36:58,516
Ah!

743
00:36:58,549 --> 00:37:00,818
Chapter 17!

744
00:37:00,851 --> 00:37:03,120
Oh, Joe!

745
00:37:03,154 --> 00:37:05,423
[cheers]

746
00:37:05,456 --> 00:37:07,091
Drunk as a skunk!

747
00:37:07,124 --> 00:37:08,859
[woman]
Oh, my God!

748
00:37:08,893 --> 00:37:13,364
Oh, how I measured the heads
of 1,000 Chippewa Indians...

749
00:37:13,397 --> 00:37:15,266
in zero weather!

